        <h1 id="skills">Skills</h1>
        <p>
          Where multiple scalable dimensions are given, a certain
          skill level only applies to one, i.e. of multiple dimensions
          shall be increased, multiple skill levels must be available.
          Specialties apply as per "original" rules, in particular at
          higher levels, for each skill.  The source for the skill names
          is <em>Harnmaster 3</em>.
        </p>
        <h3 id="learn">Learning</h3>
        <p>
          Learning is modelled by succeeding an active roll with level
          <n0/> against a passive level of the current skill.  Note that
          rolling 10 non-stop events can be shortened into rolling a
          <n1/> with a <d10/>.  Learning is not applicable to attributes.
        </p>
        <p>          
          Such rolls may be made once a month in which the skill was used
          reasonably often. Usually only three such rolls apply. A
          <em>combined</em> roll with the <em>SB</em> is made, with a bonus
          for equal skill of <n5/> (see the main page on <em>Combination</em>).
          A teacher can also be combined with his own skill - <n10/> and a
          bonus (row index) of <n5/>.  This assumes that the teacher is
          available almost always during that time.
        </p>
        <p>
          <b>Example:</b> Suppose your skill is at <n5/>, your teacher has a
          skill of <n12/> and your SB is a <n3/>.  According to the rules, we
          should first take the highest of the three parameters to be
          combined into a single skill roll.  That is <n3/> and <n2/>
          (<n12/> - <n10/>).  The third is <n0/>.  Taking the difference of
          the first two, we have a column index of <n1/> into the combination
          table and we read in the fifth row a <n4/>, which will be added to <n3/>
          (the higher of the two numbers) to yield a <n7/>. To add in the 
          third (<n0/>), we take the difference again (<n7/>) as column index
          and find in the fifth row a <n2/> that is added to the previous
          result (<n7/>) for a total of <n9/>.  That is the active skill
          level to roll against your current skill level (<n5/>) to improvex.
          We are pitting a <n9/> against a <n5/> with roughly an 80% chance
          of success and upon success the skill level is inceased to <n6/>.
        </p>
        <p>
          If a more pragmatic approach is desired, use the following "reversed"
          table for finding the addition.
        </p>
        <table>
          <tr>
            <th>Difference</th><td>0</td><td>1-2</td><td>3-4</td><td>5-8</td><td>9-13</td><td>14+</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th>Bonus</th><td>5</td><td>4</td><td>3</td><td>2</td><td>1</td><td>0</td>
          </tr>
        </table>
        <h4 id="special">Specialization</h4>
        <p>
          Skills listed as specialization are treated as <em>Decomposition</em>
          from the main rules. Learning (q.v.) should be applied to the
          main/average skill. If so desired, specializations may be learned
          separately, but the restrictions on decomposition applies and the
          number of rolls for learning each month. 
        </p>
