        <h3 id="know">Knowledge</h3>
        <p>
          The description is based on the <em>expected</em> outcome,
          i.e. simply read the result rolled as index row in the table.
        </p>
        <ul class="explain">
          <li>
            <b>Level 0:</b> NN barely knows that a domain for such
            knowledge exists.  With some luck, he can guess whether a
            general topic belongs to that domain or not.
          </li>
          <li>
            <b>Level 5:</b> A single topic, one of the most obvious
            ones has been heard of and can be applied, but without
            guaranteed success.
          </li>
          <li>
            <b>Level 10:</b> With this level, the basic concepts are
            known, the more esoteric concepts have been heard of but
            cannot be applied.
          </li>
          <li>
            <b>Level 15:</b> Most concepts are known and many can be
            applied with a high degree of certainty. There are still
            areas which can be polished.
          </li>
          <li>
            <b>Level 20:</b> All concepts of the domain are known and
            can be applied with confidence.  There are only a few
            topics escaping the grasps of this expert.
          </li>
          <li>
            <b>Level 25:</b> All of the domain is understood with ease.
            It is hard to find unknown territory, although it exists.
            Improvement of the art can be conducted.
          </li>
          <li>
            <b>Level 30:</b> Mastery of the subject matter as far as
            humanly possible.  Genuine research or creation of new
            substance is possible.
          </li>
        </ul>
        <h4 id="folklore">Folklore</h4>
        <p>
          Specializations are <em>Barbarians, Recent History, History,
          Antiquity, Off-Harn, Creatures</em>, which should be treated as separate
          skills.
        </p>
        <h3 id="com">Communication</h3>
        <p>
          The description is based on the <em>expected</em> outcome,
          i.e. simply read the result rolled as index row in the table.
          When refering to patterns in the table, this applies to
          instruments (melodies and the like) for music skills as well
          as words (word order, flection, ...). Every communication skill
          has such pattern, by which communication is encoded and decoded.
        </p>
        <ul class="explain">
          <li>
            <b>Level 0:</b> NN barely knows that a domain for such
            communication exists.  Instinctively, he is wrong as often
            as he is right when judging others.
          </li>
          <li>
            <b>Level 5:</b> A single pattern, one of the most obvious
            ones can be applied, but without guaranteed success.
          </li>
          <li>
            <b>Level 10:</b> With this level, basic patterns are
            known, the more esoteric patterns have been heard of but
            cannot be applied.
          </li>
          <li>
            <b>Level 15:</b> Most patterns are known and many can be
            applied with a high degree of certainty. There are still
            areas which can be polished.
          </li>
          <li>
            <b>Level 20:</b> All patterns of the domain are known and
            can be applied with confidence.  There are only a few
            topics escaping the grasps of this expert.
          </li>
          <li>
            <b>Level 25:</b> All of the domain is communicated with ease.
            It is hard to find unknown territory, although it exists.
            Improvement of the art can be conducted.
          </li>
          <li>
            <b>Level 30:</b> Mastery of the subject matter as far as
            humanly possible.  Genuine research or creation of new
            patterns is possible.
          </li>
        </ul>
